<font color="#FF0000">ANTI-WAR  ACCOMPLISHMENTS</font><br>
<tt>Thu Jan  8  5:21:47 US/Eastern 1998
</tt><p>
WHAT THE ANTI-WAR MOVEMENT ACCOMPLISHED IN VIETNAM<br><br>
Vietnam Insight, Vol VI, No. 7, July 1995<br><br>
The Unexposed Side of Vietnam<br><br>
Dear world, can anyone imagine? <br>
Words of the famous dissident poet Nguyen Chi Thien came to mind when I watched the two films on prison camp Z30 in Ham Tan and the mass demonstration in Hue, May 1993, to protest the arrest of a leading monk. <br>
There on the big screen, the plight of my Vietnamese compatriots unfold vividly: thousands of human souls and bodies of mostly young men and women are inhumanely and idiotically wasted in the communist gulag. The prisoners' young face indicate they had nothing to do with the Vietnam War of the past. Many must have grown up under the current communist regime. Then why under a regime that professes love and reconciliation, there are so many of its own people imprisoned and treated harshly? If the regime is by the people, for the people and of the people, why doesn't it respect the people's most basic rights? Religious leaders, especially those of the Unified Buddhist Church in Vietnam have been jailed in scores. All for what crime? <br>
These peace-loving, simple people need nothing more than a life with respect and dignity. Yet they are deprived of all that, physically and spiritually. Can it be that peaceful asking to have returned one's inalienable rights be a crime in this time and age, in a country that tries to project itself as a civilized society? <br>
The political prisoners Hanoi vehemently denies holding, the religious suppression Hanoi says never takes place, are some of many unexposed and ugly sides of Vietnam the communist rulers try hard to shield from the rest of the world. Yet the sad reality is that the record of prisoners in the past 20 years surpasses that of any point in the country's history under foreign domination. <br>
At the time Vietnam needs as many hands as possible for the rebuilding of the country, the are so many locked behind bars, exploited and punished for the &quot;crime&quot; of demanding back their rights. As the rest of the world rides the technology wave to enter the 21st century, the Vietnamese are chopping down trees and clearing jungles, even mine-fields, by hand, enduring long working hours under extreme heat and the harshest living conditions. <br>
Both films released with the pseudo-approval of the communist government -- the Z30 concentration camp was filmed at the insistence of a French reporter, and the Hue 1993 mass demonstration was filmed by the Hanoi government itself and shown throughout the country to portray how &quot;violent&quot; were the Buddhist leaders and Hue protestors -- apparently had the truth and damaging scenes filtered. Yet the two films still aroused the ire of the more than 1,000 Vietnamese surrounding me, many wiping away tears while chanting &quot;down with communism.&quot; <br>
It is in the interest and conscience of every Vietnamese to insure that this ugly side of Vietnam be exposed to the rest of the world. And it is in every human being's interest to see to it that this ugly scene in Vietnam and anywhere else in the world be put to an end. No one with a conscience can turn a blind eye to the ongoing humiliation in Vietnam and claim &quot;what Vietnamese need is food first.&quot; <br>
The dissident poet's words keep flashing in my mind: <br><br>
Because mankind, too busy, pays no mind<br>
to swamps where people, foundering, thrash and writhe,<br>
because the Communists, by foul design,<br>
use time to wear us down,<br>
doom us to live out life as beats,<br>
O history, we can no longer wait.<br>
You are a turtle, slow and dumb,<br>
and human life is short -- those who have lost<br>
must now act quick and spark a fire. <br><br>
Ending the repressive system in Vietnam is the only way to nurture the Vietnamese people both physically and spiritually. The only way to end the Vietnamese suffering and to restore their rightful dignity is to campaign for freedom now. The Vietnamese are ready to live as free people. Shall those with freedom help those without? <br>

